China's investment dependence
Beijing— In the second quarter of this year, China's economy unexpectedly slowed down.
It was equally unexpected that most of the data released since July showed that China's growth had stabilized.
It was no surprise that the market breathed a collective sigh of relief.
But should investors continue to be on high alert?
Currently, the most severe problem faced by the Chinese authorities is overcapacity.
For instance, China's crude steel capacity is 1 billion tons, but the total output in 2012 was only 0.72 billion tons — a capacity utilization rate of 72%.
Notably, the profit margin of the steel industry in 2012 was only 0.04%.
In fact, the profit obtained from producing one ton of steel can only buy a stick of gum.
As of now this year, the average profit margin of the top 500 Chinese companies is 4.34%, a 33 basis point decrease from 2012.
Some say today's overcapacity comes from past overinvestment.
Others believe overcapacity is due to insufficient effective demand.
The government's view seems to be a compromise between the two.
On the one hand, the authorities are asking thousands of companies to reduce their capacity.
On the other hand, the government has introduced some "mini stimulus" measures, such as exempting "micro-enterprises" from business tax and sales tax, and requiring banks to increase loans to export-oriented enterprises, etc.
The official stance is that China's growth model needs to reduce investment and increase consumption.
However, not all Chinese economists agree with this point.
They believe that capital stock is a key factor in growth, and China's per capita capital stock is still relatively low compared to developed countries, indicating a large amount of future investment space.
Indeed, capital accumulation is a major driver of economic growth, and catching up with the income levels of developed countries requires China to increase its capital stock over the long term.
What matters most is not the scale of capital stock, nor even the level of investment; what matters is the growth rate of investment, which has been significantly higher than the GDP growth rate for decades.
According to official statistical numbers, China's investment rate has approached 50% of its GDP.
Due to absorption constraints, capital efficiency has steadily declined with increasing capital scale.
If environmental degradation caused by rapidly growing investment is taken into account, China's capital efficiency would be even lower.
The role of human capital and technological progress in economic growth is no less than that of physical capital and labor.
If resources are allocated towards physical capital at the expense of human capital accumulation, which is a necessary condition for full consumption – and this, in turn, would lead to a slowdown in economic growth rather than an acceleration.
Therefore, China should lower its investment growth rate, raise its consumption growth rate, and let the investment rate stabilize at a more sustainable level.
Of course, saying that China's overcapacity reflects a shortage of effective demand is not entirely wrong either.
But where does effective demand come from?
In this regard, China's steel industry has provided a good example again.
Although China has no comparative advantage in steel production, it still built about a thousand steel plants, accounting for half of the world's total output.
As early as 2004, the Chinese government attempted to curb excessive investment; however, due to the strong demand generated by infrastructure investment and real estate development, output continued to grow rapidly, increasing from 3 billion tons in 2004 to 10 billion tons in 2012.
China's investments can be roughly divided into three categories: manufacturing, infrastructure, and the real estate industry.
The economic stimulus brought about by infrastructure investment sustained output growth during the peak of the global financial crisis in late 2008 and early 2009.
In 2010, real estate development investment replaced infrastructure investment as the primary driver of growth.
Today, both infrastructure and real estate are important drivers of China's growth.
China indeed needs more infrastructure investment – particularly in power and hydroelectricity, transportation, and communications.
However, the investment pace must fully take into account financial constraints.
More importantly, China can and should invest more in schools, hospitals, nursing homes, and other social infrastructure.
But real estate investment is a different story.
It is difficult to judge the severity of China's real estate bubble and when it will burst.
But one thing is certain: China has invested too much in real estate development.
China's per capita income is less than $6,000, but the homeownership rate is around 90%, while it is less than 70% in the United States.
The average living space per capita is 32.9 square meters, while it is just over 48 square meters for the median household in Hong Kong.
China has 696 five-star hotels, with another 500 under construction.
Five of the ten tallest buildings currently under construction are located in China.
In my view, this can only be described as madness.
China's economy is being hijacked by real estate investment.
On the one hand, China should not solve its overcapacity problem by maintaining a high growth rate of real estate investment.
Social housing projects are worth welcoming, but the current real estate investment of up to 10-13% of GDP has become too high.
On the other hand, if real estate investment growth slows down, the overcapacity will not be eliminated.
This highlights the structural adjustment challenges China is facing – and should also keep investors cautious.
In short, there are two things worth watching out for.
Firstly, unlike other types of investment, real estate investment does not increase the stock of productive capital.
Houses and expensive durable consumer goods are fundamentally no different.
Secondly, in China's statistical data, the growth rate of total fixed asset investment is significantly higher than the growth rate of total capital formation.
This indicates that the growth rate data of fixed investment may have exaggerated the speed of capital stock accumulation.
Therefore, although the Chinese government should resolutely reduce the economy's dependence on investment for growth, the action must be very cautious.
